\section*{Problem Statement}

A uniform spherical ball of mass $m$ rolls without slipping down a wedge of mass $M$ and angle $\alpha$, which itself can slide without friction on a horizontal table. The system moves in the plane shown in Fig. 7.12. Here $g$ denotes the gravitational acceleration. 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Find the Lagrangian and the equations of motion for this system.
    \item[(b)] For the special case of $M = m$ and $\alpha = \pi/4$, find:
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item[(i)] the acceleration of the wedge,
        \item[(ii)] the acceleration of the ball relative to the wedge.
    \end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Useful information:} Moment of inertia of a uniform sphere of mass $m$ and radius $R$ is $I = \frac{2}{5}mR^2$.

\section*{Solution}

This is obviously a two degree of freedom dynamical system. The square of the particle velocity can be written as:

\begin{equation}
    v^2 = \dot{r}^2 + (r\dot{\theta})^2
\end{equation}

Formula (1) can be derived from Cartesian coordinates:

\begin{align*}
    x &= r \cos \theta, \\
    y &= r \sin \theta, \\
    \dot{x} &= \dot{r} \cos \theta - r \dot{\theta} \sin \theta, \\
    \dot{y} &= \dot{r} \sin \theta + r \dot{\theta} \cos \theta.
\end{align*}

